 to cover the success path for `ClassLoader#getResourceAsStream`. The reporting might only detect call sites dynamically when the method is called, focusing on how resources are retrieved.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering ClassLoader resource issues**\\n\\nI’m noting that if the resource isn’t found, the agent might not output it for the ClassLoader path \\\"/ssl-config-test-keystore.p12,\\\" though the relevant call site could still be covered. It seems that the resource coverage might only count successfully loaded resources. This leads me to wonder if `Class#getResourceAsStream` could return null in tests if the resource is absent, possibly due to Gradle not executing processResources. The Java plugin should include this step. So, I need clarity on the execution process!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating test source structure**\\n\\nI'm wrestling with the target test source root issue. It seems the resource needs to be under `src/test/resources`, but I'm not sure if adding resources violates any guidelines. The user's guidance mentions something about the resolved target test source root. However, I’m considering that resources may not usually be included in the Java directory. I might need to think of alternatives like generating a classpath resource or creating a file under `src/test/java`, but that might complicate things.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Examining resource loading issues**\\n\\nI'm trying to cover the `Class#getResourceAsStream` method, but it seems to falter with a `KeyStore.load` IOException. I'm considering whether it's valid to assert a negative path, especially when passing a non-keystore resource results in a `CertificateException`. Is that a supported negative case? I can avoid using a resource file by using a class file as a resource path instead. The question is whether this unique approach meets coverage requirements and if it's acceptable to have invalid keystore contents in the test.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring resource handling in tests**\\n\\nI'm considering whether I can create a temporary directory with resources at runtime and use a custom context classloader to ensure success. However, there's the issue with native dynamic resources. When using the defining class's loader, it looks like `Class#getResourceAsStream` delegates to it instead of the context classloader. I wonder if I could generate a resource file in the class output, but it seems like the source root rules might not forbid using `src/test/resources` for this purpose.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating keytool usage**\\n\\nI’m thinking about the keytool and whether the generated resource includes a timestamp and machine info. It looks like it doesn’t. I wonder if I can avoid the binary by generating the keystore in test resources through a `TestExecutionListener`. But it seems that won't work either. Maybe writing a base64 resource could help, but REST Assured needs the KeyStore. I think only adding `src/test/resources` might be the way to go. I don't really need to read the dynamic report for uncovered items, unless the active class already has an existing coverage file.\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "Implemented focused coverage for `io.restassured.config.SSLConfig`.\n\nChanges made:\n- Added `tests/src/io.rest-assured/rest-assured/5.5.0/src/test/java/io_rest_assured/rest_assured/SSLConfigTest.java`\n  - Exercises `SSLConfig.keyStore(String, String)` with an absolute classpath resource path.\n  - Calls `relaxedHTTPSValidation(\"TLS\")`, which reaches `SSLConfig.loadKeyStore()`.\n  - The leading slash path causes:\n    - `Thread.currentThread().getContextClassLoader().getResourceAsStream(...)` to be invoked first.\n    - Fallback to `getClass().getResourceAsStream(...)` to load the keystore.\n- Added test keystore resource:\n  - `tests/src/io.rest-assured/rest-assured/5.5.0/src/test/resources/ssl-config-test-keystore.p12`\n\nI did not compile or run tests, per instructions.", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_01abd7c6dc3ddf4b016a26cfce27708190b2e2735280b50445\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 347, "output": 1544, "cacheRead": 23040, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 24931, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "stop", "timestamp": 1780928425797, "responseId": "resp_01abd7c6dc3ddf4b016a26cfaa48ec81908d5d1591eb7afe4e"}}
[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating metadata and resources**\n\nI'm considering whether untracked metadata existed previously and whether it should be removed. It seems this current worktree may have generated files that might not be ours. If asked, we could claim we didn't create anything, but proving that could be tough. Checking git status might help, but modifying metadata shouldn’t happen. I also want to look for potential issues with test resources, especially regarding how they get included or accessed dynamically. No editing resources in META-INF, right?\n\n**Analyzing ClassLoader issues**\n\nI'm thinking there might be a potential issue with whether the ClassLoader in a native image supports a leading slash. It might still be called, even if it returns null. If the resource isn't in the native image before metadata generation, that could be problematic. The agent captures resources on the JVM classpath during the test. I wonder if I need to cover the success path for `ClassLoader#getResourceAsStream`. The reporting might only detect call sites dynamically when the method is called, focusing on how resources are retrieved.\n\n**Considering ClassLoader resource issues**\n\nI’m noting that if the resource isn’t found, the agent might not output it for the ClassLoader path \"/ssl-config-test-keystore.p12,\" though the relevant call site could still be covered. It seems that the resource coverage might only count successfully loaded resources. This leads me to wonder if `Class#getResourceAsStream` could return null in tests if the resource is absent, possibly due to Gradle not executing processResources. The Java plugin should include this step. So, I need clarity on the execution process!\n\n**Evaluating test source structure**\n\nI'm wrestling with the target test source root issue. It seems the resource needs to be under `src/test/resources`, but I'm not sure if adding resources violates any guidelines. The user's guidance mentions something about the resolved target test source root. However, I’m considering that resources may not usually be included in the Java directory. I might need to think of alternatives like generating a classpath resource or creating a file under `src/test/java`, but that might complicate things.\n\n**Examining resource loading issues**\n\nI'm trying to cover the `Class#getResourceAsStream` method, but it seems to falter with a `KeyStore.load` IOException. I'm considering whether it's valid to assert a negative path, especially when passing a non-keystore resource results in a `CertificateException`. Is that a supported negative case? I can avoid using a resource file by using a class file as a resource path instead. The question is whether this unique approach meets coverage requirements and if it's acceptable to have invalid keystore contents in the test.\n\n**Exploring resource handling in tests**\n\nI'm considering whether I can create a temporary directory with resources at runtime and use a custom context classloader to ensure success. However, there's the issue with native dynamic resources. When using the defining class's loader, it looks like `Class#getResourceAsStream` delegates to it instead of the context classloader. I wonder if I could generate a resource file in the class output, but it seems like the source root rules might not forbid using `src/test/resources` for this purpose.\n\n**Evaluating keytool usage**\n\nI’m thinking about the keytool and whether the generated resource includes a timestamp and machine info. It looks like it doesn’t. I wonder if I can avoid the binary by generating the keystore in test resources through a `TestExecutionListener`. But it seems that won't work either. Maybe writing a base64 resource could help, but REST Assured needs the KeyStore. I think only adding `src/test/resources` might be the way to go. I don't really need to read the dynamic report for uncovered items, unless the active class already has an existing coverage file.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_01abd7c6dc3ddf4b016a26cfaafd2c8190bd7b4a679c358d10\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqJs_OVmlrCdj_qwOpm3FEtjH9NGgbJ2Jh27qgycU4ihstHtVS0pdO_RwkVs8DZVzobSsgcx1byXsRg8IDi_gBenmCmBv3NCCI8lTTnPv7rEDXuJkgMcc7mwXn_RMuOmXSU1ddnBdtwRTk_70NMJJ09MSVQrbMB81wVTNIHi_f7hegea8jwV-GdZkg62RIXAFa-4WAaquKOVK4yfkhS_qfm6BWHycmZ9q7vn9SUqLxXdAU5AtSpKmE7jVGEBmXDEQTRxCV_rqGMeRt5mgRAZDO5cF1Dw7JBGrQT7zXZleC4DaMw9cf_LrnOFSN1REjaTnsuMhdf2DqGFxR0v0AKsMmoYFbq1q59stN781MmWQ5NHi8B0ipwsBUdICNfHMuTs2zQX-OwTbjhkYuw2NNjrJkuT3Y37rBZAw9305sxDRGX6lF_ANqE6D6MvqPpwGRwfXcAP3andyAtmK5NVYT2_nlsnN3FcjY6FaqpU_8MrMrUonS8D-jWEzTCtliumLm4rwa62aReWhrpfmz0Tp-FaDw_gkGwSH2-ljTbaZc8_SXkEIWOM60WQxwVByGufumBc2R8wbEwt23Icx7bgY1hvcY5GZUK2bbGFGQNA_z_2kMoLhV1GkGiAg3L7jiE1bJa5_KL61uHjsH8ETKOyU3iY2RZjKcUrXX1dmnKRCgzMNGYr1uO2TYHGEl2n-9-cKVY_I-aCsuQ-oxQ2kMGtTld1LlcZhYkftxL__w-0p2V9POWPY26wb57324GbJQtoyIed_YuLnXBoeTWcaf4Ti5nufRZg_pfj6CttBe_5TXN14iF0hahzDegP5fmS9NiW7oqeCwnIjBfFip0nVowJfn0wxxobMC2RgZNyCGzfwxVPpb0yVOKsRMSSz7Rh8_NOzpufaE9fI6ZyfP5svC9MZ-Kj4Lc-UOyHkxUu1HKIDXl0iri1K2fxbcd4QOmWJyB-B6s8Hf2vIwuqy2fMcPKn-HK0dXPiiSNcFzzAspuprweJuDQd0cIaX-YnjgV3nUlMNT62kq8D2_ValoTd1-u1fTL1Ja2kbcxrmVKcYXR7pm9SKM0CHdUYZu_mxZzyJFI-35TLO4SV6kCPhTkyOUF6EPLCwHMpixhX8ORz9xOphaaf8aAWKUg3GI3wBgBVssjWuMP7JjXXETzcampS2x4uwMhulrLIKkrzFKLGpoOZEPdxVJ65rSiHIn2BBN5H3mO0WbeSlbXrNqCCxhZ2gjATMGD_2u2s42IZvwQBV95Vq4CdREIAcMkddU1S7bAvjgvQ01Zm4ryu-u94gYw-6rUDnd4odiHDc6UZdTWZgrmi9iZwNeUI2CHlFWnyAN11Fp1KOBL3ktk5tl2V5yP-MwyJtOVhD184GGb9N9X8PRue-goa9HiDPtLoXzgyiD0Q8J7D5RvhX7yC_LDP_ckbTVQRt3lSG6P5Ir5zJussPC12bvHR0BZpcPwdX0sAQZNhjWABubTYUzsi6G3w715Liu63iokg2s7kPsCg1fP9bTYe_WWWB2gAHzKB5pM5lUcD8VJU0tf1269S1MUrVYW-FuAWPUY0AKi8QD4CA6NxMYTpYMY00xHJ2Yu0ZpFt1udnwRXJIEVXAvoMYYxAO-c-M0XeVxPq18Ii_C9r0ZsDkdU9kbkCDAVc9uYgHuR2F0NrQVhDzUukobjeDTpU9P2dL5UM0lZ2yBN3teLl9GSu2-X9fWNWuLIpVAvZwzZQ6dA-vo91Q02DbmLhw6WBwWvGuwSNOfZVRIgn9sWXPinqYb62JqzfRQFhry